I’d like to introduce you to two new friends of mine, Zephyr (first two images), and Diego (one of the Mexican Gray Wolves, finding a snack). They are two of 49 wolves residing at @wolfconservationcenter in South Salem, NY, just an hour north of NYC. The folks at WCC are doing crucial work through their science-based education for the public, and participating in the federal recovery & release programs for the Red Wolf and Mexican Gray Wolf species, both of which are critically endangered. While the statistics for these animals worldwide may be depressing, the amazing progress at WCC is reason for hope — and the very day I visited, a brand new Red Wolf arrived named Lava, who will soon be a new girlfriend for Tyke, to help create the next generation. If you’re in the area, definitely sign up for a program to visit, or simply donate online to help them continue the important work they do.
.
.
.
.

Rest In Powder, Jake. Vermont lost a pioneer last night — Jake Burton Carpenter was a visionary, a pillar of the VT/BTV community, and the founder of a sport that put a smile on so many peoples faces all winter long. I was fortunate enough to spend some brief time with Jake on a handful of occasions and I will never forget the quick snowy hike/ride we did with Donna and their dogs for this photo session; and how warm, kind, and genuinely rad this guy was to everyone around him. #RideonJake.
.
.

Fun little assignment for @wsj, shooting (and riding in) this incredibly rare 1936 LG45 Lagonda owned by Desmond Fitzgeral. Desmond has owned nine total, buying & selling throughout his life starting with his first which he drove while at Harvard in the 1960s, and has owned four examples of the LG45 model, of which only sixteen were made.
